{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774643246,"nonce":"1VkqjrqFZV9UPA+QfvqdvwUuhFg=","message":"Ambiguity clarification for the issue body:\n\n\"This is the primary test of whether adversarial training produces genuinely robust controllers\" — in the Part 1 context (no SISU), \"adversarial training\" is ambiguous. Part 1 models are trained with standard backprop (no minimax, no CVaR, no APT) at varying perturbation amplitudes (pert_std). The phrase \"adversarial training\" here should read \"training with perturbations\" or \"perturbation-exposed training.\" These are standard-backprop PAI-ASF models evaluated under curl fields, not minimax-trained models.\n\n\"Compare models trained at different perturbation std levels\" — the architecture is unspecified, but in the Part 1 context these are GRU 180-hidden models with no SISU input (Part 1 predates the SISU integration). The specific pert_std values depend on the model set loaded at analysis time.\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}